## Critical Inspection Checklist (Before You Pay)

Whether new or second-hand, inspect these items before committing:

### Refrigeration Unit
- Run the unit for minimum 30 minutes (check temperature drops as expected)
- Listen for unusual noises (grinding, squealing = compressor or bearing issues)
- Check compressor hours (under 5,000 hours is ideal for second-hand)
- Verify temperature calibration with independent thermometer
- Test door seals (close a piece of paper in the door — should resist gentle pull)
- Inspect for refrigerant leaks (oily residue around pipes and fittings)

### Insulation and Body
- Check for moisture damage (dark spots, soft panels = insulation failure)
- Inspect floor condition (corrosion, delamination)
- Verify door hinges and latches operate smoothly
- Check curtain sides or side doors seal properly
- Look for previous accident repairs (uneven panel gaps, paint mismatch)

### Chassis
- Full service history (especially for second-hand)
- Engine compression test if high mileage
- Check for oil leaks under the truck
- Test drive (transmission smooth, brakes responsive)
- Tire condition and age (cracked sidewalls = replacement needed)

### Documentation
- Puspakom inspection (mandatory for transfer)
- Road tax validity
- Insurance coverage
- Previous maintenance records (crucial for second-hand)
- Refrigeration unit service history

**Pro tip:** Don't inspect alone if you're new to cold chain. Bring a mechanic who knows refrigeration units, or hire an independent inspection service.

