## Common Mistakes to Avoid

### 1. Underestimating Power Requirements
A supplier says "this truck maintains -18°C." What they don't say is "when the engine is running at 2,000 RPM and ambient temperature is 25°C."

Reality: Malaysian afternoons hit 35°C+. Multiple door openings during deliveries heat the load. Your refrigeration unit needs margin.

**Rule of thumb:** Size your refrigeration unit 20-30% larger than your theoretical requirement.

### 2. Not Checking Backup Power
What happens when your truck breaks down? Your product keeps thawing while waiting for repairs.

**Better:** Plan for backup cold storage relationships with warehouses along your delivery routes.

### 3. Ignoring Temperature Monitoring Technology
Old school: Check thermometer at delivery end, realize product spoiled.

New school: Real-time alerts to your phone when temperature deviates.

**ROI:** One prevented spoilage incident pays for the monitoring system.

### 4. Choosing the Wrong Body Configuration
Single compartment when you need frozen AND chilled? Door on the wrong side for your warehouse loading dock?

**Tip:** Map your actual loading/unloading workflow before choosing body layout. Ask the supplier to show you similar setups in use.

### 5. Forgoing Regular Maintenance
Refrigeration units that skip scheduled maintenance have 3x higher failure rates.

**Schedule:** Every 200 hours or 6 months, whichever comes first. More often in tropical climate.

